"Yes, sir. They should already be on their way; we gave them time to pack food from the cafeteria." At 05:00, Exodus Company gathered in the vehicle bay. Captain Xiao stood on a box and began speaking.
"We will head to the I-131 front-line base 50 miles outside Ianlos City. We will support the ongoing siege operation, then attack Ianlos City to clear out the rebels there. We will use this as a base to advance into the mountains." Captain Xiao explained. "Take your squad and get ready to depart."
The company dispersed, with each platoon boarding a tank under their respective platoon leaders. Keren climbed onto the front tank of the convoy and sat with Nimitz, Cress, and two new recruits. Keren remembered they had just arrived a few days ago but didn't know much about them. He sat on the edge of the tank, his legs hanging down, adjusting his backpack and radio equipment, connecting it to his earphones and throat microphone.
"Hey, Keren, does Harris still have Snowball?" Nimitz asked after they settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?" Keren recalled the morning they stole chickens from the farm. "Yes, I'm certain of it."
Keren looked at another tank and saw Harris and his team. He could vaguely see a small chicken peering around behind Harris's backpack.
"Yes, he's still keeping that chicken," Keren replied. At that moment, the hatch of the tank turret opened with a loud bang, and the platoon leader appeared before them.
"All tanks are underway," the platoon leader said calmly and clearly into his earpiece. The armored platoon's tanks and Stryker armored vehicles roared to life and began moving forward. Keren's Cronostank released its brakes and moved forward, joining the formation. The tanks formed a wedge formation as they crossed the Iteania Plain. Winter storms had frozen the wetlands and forests, but the mud remained.
About an hour later, a new recruit (Keren remembered his name was奥斯恩) spoke up, "Captain, have you been on the front line since the start of the conflict?"
"Yes, since the Firestorm operation began," Keren answered. "We thought the battle would be over in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"They underestimated us by more than just a little," Nimitz joined in the conversation. "Their weapons and forces exceeded our expectations. They shot down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and the Erebus last month. Damnit, we should have seen it on the way."
"Well, I'll bravely fight for the federation," Osen said firmly. "I won't be intimidated by those terrorists."
"You say that now, but from what I've seen, most new recruits like you tend to pee their pants at the sound of gunfire," Cres said.
"We'll see about that," Keren smiled. Osen didn't say anything else.
"Exodus Deputy Commander! Exodus Commander!" Keren's radio device chirped. "We've detected a heat signature 20 degrees and 350 yards to our right front."
Keren climbed into the tank and put on his optical goggles. After switching to thermal imaging mode, he saw a heat signature in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," Keren said into his throat microphone.
"Are they enemies?" another new recruit, Natalia, asked.
"Can't tell yet," Keren replied, turning on the microphone. "Exodus Company, unless attacked, do not fire. Bring them out first."
As they got closer, the faint heat signature transformed from a blurry dot into a clearer outline. One of them ran towards something, picked something up, and ran back to the ridge. Then, these people lay down and took up firing positions.
"We've encountered enemies!" Major Xiang shouted over the radio as orange tracers flew up from the ridge. Bullets pinged off the sides of the tank, and the assault team jumped down, hiding behind the vehicle. A反坦克导弹 whistled past, exploding behind the tank column, fragments hitting one of the M1A2 Abrams tanks. Another missile hit the side of an M113 armored personnel carrier (APS-Cerberus) and exploded. The crew inside scrambled out, seeking cover as their ammunition detonated.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 yards. Fire!" the tank platoon leader ordered via radio. The main guns of Iron 1-2 and 1-3 roared to life, shells whizzing toward the ridge, explosions sending dirt and debris flying into the air.
"Send out sentry robots!" Knox called, looking through his binoculars at the ridge. The rear hatch of a M240B "Hellhound" opened, and a soldier without weapons stepped out, wearing special earphones. He shouted commands into a square microphone, and two "sentry" robots emerged. Their long metal arms and legs swung forward as they ran quickly. The robots were armed but had the weapons slung on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" Cress asked, observing.
"Looks like we're taking him alive," Keren guessed, watching as the two sentry robots disappeared into the smoke and ash. Hails of shouts and gunfire echoed from the ridge but soon subsided. After a while, the two sentry robots returned, dragging a man with them. The boots of the prisoner left a trail in the mud and snow. Once safely back, the robots dumped the captive onto the ground, where he landed hard in the mud and snow, groaning in pain.
He struggled to stand up, and Captain Xiao approached. Captain Xiao turned to one of the sentry robots. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," the sentry robot replied. "The rest have fled on foot."
Captain Xiao nodded and turned towards Keren and Crees standing nearby, saying, "Can you two take this person away?"
